abstract: Has the Trump Department of Justice ever asked for a lower sentence for someone who wasn’t a presidential ally?
snippet: Has the Trump Department of Justice ever asked for a lower sentence for someone who wasn’t a presidential ally?
lead_paragraph: After much sound and fury, Roger Stone — Trump ally, Nixon devotee and longtime political mischief-maker — was sentenced on Thursday to 40 months in federal prison for lying to Congress and witness tampering. Despite what President Trump has claimed, both the career prosecutors and the judge in the case ensured justice was served. Attorney General William Barr’s actions in the days leading up to the sentencing, on the other hand, appropriately sent a chill down the spines of prosecutors across the country.

abstract: President Donald Trump’s reelection campaign and the Republican National Committee announced Thursday that they will spend more than $10 million during the 2020 election cycle to battle Democrats on voting-related lawsuits and to bolster their Election Day operations.
snippet: President Donald Trump’s reelection campaign and the Republican National Committee announced Thursday that they will spend more than $10 million during the 2020 election cycle to battle Democrats on voting-related lawsuits and to bolster their Ele...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Donald Trump’s reelection campaign and the Republican National Committee announced Thursday that they will spend more than $10 million during the 2020 election cycle to battle Democrats on voting-related lawsuits and to bolster their Election Day operations.
headline_main: Trump Campaign, RNC to Spend $10M on Voting Lawsuits
headline_print_headline: Trump Campaign, RNC to Spend $10M on Voting Lawsuits

abstract: British Prime Minister Boris Johnson is looking forward to meeting U.S. President Donald Trump in June, Johnson's office said after reports that an expected meeting between the two leaders in early 2020 had been postponed.
snippet: British Prime Minister Boris Johnson is looking forward to meeting U.S. President Donald Trump in June, Johnson's office said after reports that an expected meeting between the two leaders in early 2020 had been postponed.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — British Prime Minister Boris Johnson is looking forward to meeting U.S. President Donald Trump in June, Johnson's office said after reports that an expected meeting between the two leaders in early 2020 had been postponed.
headline_main: UK PM Johnson Says Looking Forward to Meeting Trump in June
headline_print_headline: UK PM Johnson Says Looking Forward to Meeting Trump in June

abstract: The United States and India are unlikely to reach a limited trade agreement in time for U.S. President Donald Trump's visit to India next week as proposed new Indian tariffs have complicated negotiations, the head of a U.S.-based business group said on Thursday.
snippet: The United States and India are unlikely to reach a limited trade agreement in time for U.S. President Donald Trump's visit to India next week as proposed new Indian tariffs have complicated negotiations, the head of a U.S.-based business group sa...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States and India are unlikely to reach a limited trade agreement in time for U.S. President Donald Trump's visit to India next week as proposed new Indian tariffs have complicated negotiations, the head of a U.S.-based business group said on Thursday.
headline_main: U.S.-India Trade Deal Unlikely Before Trump's India Trip: Business Group
headline_print_headline: U.S.-India Trade Deal Unlikely Before Trump's India Trip: Business Group

abstract: The notion of banning fracking is dividing the Democrats running for president and increasingly dividing Democrats in the presidential battleground state of Pennsylvania, where fracking has vaulted it to the No. 2 natural gas producer behind Texas.
snippet: The notion of banning fracking is dividing the Democrats running for president and increasingly dividing Democrats in the presidential battleground state of Pennsylvania, where fracking has vaulted it to the No. 2 natural gas producer behind Texas...
lead_paragraph: HARRISBURG, Pa. — The notion of banning fracking is dividing the Democrats running for president and increasingly dividing Democrats in the presidential battleground state of Pennsylvania, where fracking has vaulted it to the No. 2 natural gas producer behind Texas.
headline_main: Fracking Debate Causes Tremors in Battleground Pennsylvania
headline_print_headline: Fracking Debate Causes Tremors in Battleground Pennsylvania

abstract: Expelling Wall Street Journal reporters returns China to a darker age.
snippet: Expelling Wall Street Journal reporters returns China to a darker age.
lead_paragraph: Several years ago, in an overheated room in Beijing, I was forced to endure a stern lecture from a Chinese foreign ministry official. My sin: As the editor at The Wall Street Journal responsible for the paper’s overseas opinion sections, I had apparently insulted the entire Chinese people by publishing the work of a “well-known terrorist” — the courageous Uighur human-rights activist Rebiya Kadeer.

abstract: Nigeria asked the United States on Thursday to abandon new visa restrictions on the West African country set to take effect on Feb. 21.
snippet: Nigeria asked the United States on Thursday to abandon new visa restrictions on the West African country set to take effect on Feb. 21.
lead_paragraph: ABUJA — Nigeria asked the United States on Thursday to abandon new visa restrictions on the West African country set to take effect on Feb. 21.

abstract: Former New York Mayor Mike Bloomberg has plunged over $400 million of his personal fortune into his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, an astronomical sum that has led many of his rivals to charge that he is trying to buy the crown.
snippet: Former New York Mayor Mike Bloomberg has plunged over $400 million of his personal fortune into his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, an astronomical sum that has led many of his rivals to charge that he is trying to buy the cro...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Former New York Mayor Mike Bloomberg has plunged over $400 million of his personal fortune into his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, an astronomical sum that has led many of his rivals to charge that he is trying to buy the crown.
